WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.630 --> 00:00:02.213
Prof: Okay.
 

00:00:02.213 --> 00:00:03.380
Good morning,
ladies and gentlemen.

00:00:03.380 --> 00:00:06.736
My name is Craig Wright and
this is "Listening to

00:00:06.736 --> 00:00:10.283
Music," the most basic
course that the Department of

00:00:10.283 --> 00:00:11.740
Music has to offer.
 

00:00:11.740 --> 00:00:14.660
Its aim is to teach you how to
listen to music.

00:00:14.660 --> 00:00:16.430
"Wait a minute,"
you say.

00:00:16.430 --> 00:00:17.990
"That's preposterous.
 

00:00:17.990 --> 00:00:20.170
I listen to music all the time.
 

00:00:20.170 --> 00:00:23.593
I've got, what,
my iPod, I'm downloading mp3

00:00:23.593 --> 00:00:26.460
files, continually swapping
files.

00:00:26.460 --> 00:00:29.140
I've got my car..."
 

00:00:29.140 --> 00:00:31.750
(What do we call those things
in the automobile where you--

00:00:31.750 --> 00:00:34.880
Is it a DAT tape that you can
take your iPod and plug it in to

00:00:34.880 --> 00:00:37.141
the--
your--the stereo system in your

00:00:37.141 --> 00:00:37.510
car?)
 

00:00:37.510 --> 00:00:38.184
"I've got that.
 

00:00:38.184 --> 00:00:39.837
I listen to music in my dorm
room off my computer,

00:00:39.837 --> 00:00:40.850
in the bookstore,
wherever.

00:00:40.850 --> 00:00:44.378
I bet I listen to a lot more
music than you do,

00:00:44.378 --> 00:00:45.990
you old goat."
 

00:00:45.990 --> 00:00:47.630
And you're right.
 

00:00:47.630 --> 00:00:49.140
You probably do.
 

00:00:49.140 --> 00:00:52.710
But what kind of music are you
listening to?

00:00:52.710 --> 00:00:55.040
Well, probably pop music and
that's fine;

00:00:55.040 --> 00:00:56.206
that's okay,
fair enough,

00:00:56.206 --> 00:00:56.790
pop music.
 

00:00:56.790 --> 00:01:00.551
But are you getting the most
out of this particular

00:01:00.551 --> 00:01:01.530
experience?
 

00:01:01.530 --> 00:01:06.450
Are you getting the most out of
your listening experience?

00:01:06.450 --> 00:01:10.754
I contend that perhaps you are
not, that you are not maximizing

00:01:10.754 --> 00:01:13.810
the time, using that time most
profitably.

00:01:13.810 --> 00:01:16.459
How do I know this?
 

00:01:16.459 --> 00:01:20.010
What makes me think that you
are not getting as much as you

00:01:20.010 --> 00:01:22.030
possibly can out of your music?
 

00:01:22.030 --> 00:01:24.188
Well, experience,
to some degree,

00:01:24.188 --> 00:01:27.830
but also an experiment that I
did just last weekend.

00:01:27.830 --> 00:01:29.040
I have four children.
 

00:01:29.040 --> 00:01:33.068
The last of the four has now
turned seventeen so I said last

00:01:33.068 --> 00:01:35.459
weekend--
he's always with the iPod

00:01:35.459 --> 00:01:37.700
on--"Chris,
what are you listening to?"

00:01:37.700 --> 00:01:39.019
"Go away.
 

00:01:39.019 --> 00:01:40.500
You're bothering me." Okay.
 

00:01:40.500 --> 00:01:42.000
"You're ruining my life
again."

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:44.099
So &gt;
 

00:01:44.099 --> 00:01:44.867
"Well now,
come on.

00:01:44.867 --> 00:01:45.670
Let me listen to this.
 

00:01:45.670 --> 00:01:46.170
Let me listen to it.
 

00:01:46.170 --> 00:01:47.150
What are you listening to?"
 

00:01:47.150 --> 00:01:48.530
So I listened to it and I said,
"All right.

00:01:48.530 --> 00:01:50.938
Here, you listen to this and
tell me what you're

00:01:50.938 --> 00:01:51.760
hearing."
 

00:01:51.760 --> 00:01:53.440
And what did--what was he
tracking?

00:01:53.440 --> 00:01:57.242
He was tracking the text;
he was tracking the beat of the

00:01:57.242 --> 00:01:57.810
piece.
 

00:01:57.810 --> 00:01:59.831
I asked him,
"Well, what's the mode of

00:01:59.831 --> 00:02:00.409
the piece?
 

00:02:00.409 --> 00:02:02.700
What's the meter of the piece?
 

00:02:02.700 --> 00:02:03.790
What's the bass doing?
 

00:02:03.790 --> 00:02:05.250
Can you follow the bass line
there?

00:02:05.250 --> 00:02:08.669
Can you identify any chords in
this particular piece?"

00:02:08.669 --> 00:02:10.000
Nothing. Zero.
 

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:13.715
And this from a reasonably
sophisticated kid who's had

00:02:13.715 --> 00:02:16.590
twelve years of serious cello
lessons,

00:02:16.590 --> 00:02:19.685
and that brings up,
I suppose, a point:

00:02:19.685 --> 00:02:24.653
that although I don't know much
about your music I think I can

00:02:24.653 --> 00:02:28.807
teach you a great deal about
your music by using the

00:02:28.807 --> 00:02:31.658
paradigms of classical music.
 

00:02:31.658 --> 00:02:34.498
So I'm going to tell you a lot
about classical music in here:

00:02:34.498 --> 00:02:35.729
Mozart, Bach,
Beethoven.

00:02:35.729 --> 00:02:38.889
It will be the locus of our
course.

00:02:38.889 --> 00:02:41.780
How many of you already listen
to classical music?

00:02:41.780 --> 00:02:42.580
Raise your hand.
 

00:02:42.580 --> 00:02:43.229
Okay. Great.
 

00:02:43.229 --> 00:02:45.210
A lot of you and that's
wonderful.

00:02:45.210 --> 00:02:47.310
I'd be interested to know,
gentleman down here,

00:02:47.310 --> 00:02:48.270
how do you do this?
 

00:02:48.270 --> 00:02:50.690
Is it streaming off of your
computer?

00:02:50.690 --> 00:02:54.009
Are you downloading mp3 files
and saving them?

00:02:54.009 --> 00:02:55.720
How--Tell me. How do you do it?
 

00:02:55.720 --> 00:02:57.080
Student: I just go to
YouTube.

00:02:57.080 --> 00:02:58.127
Prof: You go to YouTube.
 

00:02:58.127 --> 00:02:58.500
All right.
 

00:02:58.500 --> 00:02:59.520
Very interesting.
 

00:02:59.520 --> 00:03:00.900
I should have known that but I
didn't.

00:03:00.900 --> 00:03:02.449
You go to YouTube and you
listen there.

00:03:02.449 --> 00:03:05.875
Anybody else do it a different
way?

00:03:05.875 --> 00:03:06.479
Yes?
 

00:03:06.479 --> 00:03:07.259
Student: On the radio.
 

00:03:07.259 --> 00:03:08.719
Prof: On the radio. Okay.
 

00:03:08.719 --> 00:03:09.710
That's interesting.
 

00:03:09.710 --> 00:03:11.389
We'll come back to that point.
 

00:03:11.389 --> 00:03:12.688
Anything else, anybody?
 

00:03:12.688 --> 00:03:12.846
Yes?
 

00:03:12.846 --> 00:03:14.568
Student: My parents' CDs
or records.

00:03:14.568 --> 00:03:15.275
Prof: Okay.
 

00:03:15.275 --> 00:03:16.449
Your parents' CDs or records.
 

00:03:16.449 --> 00:03:17.378
That's wonderful.
 

00:03:17.378 --> 00:03:21.186
They have sort of the old
technology here but some of

00:03:21.186 --> 00:03:24.699
those old recordings might be
very, very good.

00:03:24.699 --> 00:03:26.318
Now here is a question for you.
 

00:03:26.318 --> 00:03:29.680
Why would we want to listen to
classical music?

00:03:29.680 --> 00:03:32.525
Why do--why--who just answered
a question for me,

00:03:32.525 --> 00:03:34.599
those folks who raised your
hand?

00:03:34.599 --> 00:03:36.318
What--gentleman here again.
 

00:03:36.318 --> 00:03:38.508
I'll--you're my sacrificial
lamb this morning.

00:03:38.508 --> 00:03:41.770
Why do you like to listen and
why would you want to listen to

00:03:41.770 --> 00:03:42.750
classical music?
 

00:03:42.750 --> 00:03:44.169
Student: It relaxes me.
 

00:03:44.169 --> 00:03:45.229
Prof: Okay.
 

00:03:45.229 --> 00:03:46.288
Very interesting.
 

00:03:46.288 --> 00:03:50.829
National Public Radio asked
exactly this question in a

00:03:50.829 --> 00:03:55.882
survey a year or so ago and they
got the following principal

00:03:55.882 --> 00:03:57.508
responses back.
 

00:03:57.508 --> 00:03:58.870
Why do people listen to
classical music?

00:03:58.870 --> 00:04:02.344
One, it helps them relax and
relieve stress,

00:04:02.344 --> 00:04:05.740
so this is perhaps the
principal reason.

00:04:05.740 --> 00:04:09.969
Two, it helps us center the
mind, allowing the listener to

00:04:09.969 --> 00:04:11.008
concentrate.
 

00:04:11.008 --> 00:04:15.908
Three, classical music provides
a vision of a better world,

00:04:15.908 --> 00:04:21.278
a refuge of beauty,
of majesty, perhaps of even--

00:04:21.278 --> 00:04:24.569
of love--and sometimes,
at least for me personally,

00:04:24.569 --> 00:04:27.639
it suggests that there might be
something out there,

00:04:27.639 --> 00:04:31.730
God or whatever,
bigger than ourselves,

00:04:31.730 --> 00:04:36.240
and it asks us to think
sometimes, think about things.

00:04:36.240 --> 00:04:39.735
That's what I think these great
fine arts do,

00:04:39.735 --> 00:04:42.435
great literature,
poetry, painting,

00:04:42.435 --> 00:04:43.230
music.
 

00:04:43.230 --> 00:04:47.725
They show what human beings can
be, the capacity of the human

00:04:47.725 --> 00:04:48.399
spirit.
 

00:04:48.399 --> 00:04:51.858
They suggest to us as indicated
maybe there is something,

00:04:51.858 --> 00:04:55.502
a larger spirit out there than
ourselves, and they get us to

00:04:55.502 --> 00:04:56.120
think.
 

00:04:56.120 --> 00:04:59.466
They get me to think frequently
about what I'm doing on this

00:04:59.466 --> 00:04:59.920
earth.
 

00:04:59.920 --> 00:05:02.459
What are you doing on this
earth?

00:05:02.459 --> 00:05:03.898
&gt;
 

00:05:03.898 --> 00:05:05.139
Don't answer that.
 

00:05:05.139 --> 00:05:08.505
What am I doing on this earth
with regard to this particular

00:05:08.505 --> 00:05:09.019
course?
 

00:05:09.019 --> 00:05:12.199
What am I trying to accomplish
in here?

00:05:12.199 --> 00:05:15.990
Well, maybe two things.
 

00:05:15.990 --> 00:05:21.269
One, change your personality.
 

00:05:21.269 --> 00:05:23.709
I want to make you a richer
person,

00:05:23.709 --> 00:05:28.127
a broader person,
by instilling you with an

00:05:28.127 --> 00:05:33.492
unending deep and abiding
understanding of classical

00:05:33.492 --> 00:05:35.978
music,
so that's part of this,

00:05:35.978 --> 00:05:39.269
and not just here for Yale but
for your life after Yale.

00:05:39.269 --> 00:05:44.129
I would hope that how you lead
your life ten years from now,

00:05:44.129 --> 00:05:45.819
twenty years from now,
thirty years from now,

00:05:45.819 --> 00:05:49.831
would have been significantly
influenced by this particular

00:05:49.831 --> 00:05:51.769
experience in this course.
 

00:05:51.769 --> 00:05:54.557
And secondly,
if I'm successful in my

00:05:54.557 --> 00:05:58.430
teaching I will accomplish this
second aim here.

00:05:58.430 --> 00:06:02.209
I will impart to you a love of
classical music.

00:06:02.209 --> 00:06:06.269
You, through,
later on after Yale,

00:06:06.269 --> 00:06:10.206
your attendance at concerts,
buying of one fashion or

00:06:10.206 --> 00:06:12.096
another,
downloading mp3 files,

00:06:12.096 --> 00:06:13.920
iTunes or whatever it happens
to be,

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:16.560
maybe being members of your
local symphony board,

00:06:16.560 --> 00:06:17.970
opera company,
something like that,

00:06:17.970 --> 00:06:20.649
maybe giving music lessons to
your children,

00:06:20.649 --> 00:06:25.550
you will become the purveyors
of classical music thereafter.

00:06:25.550 --> 00:06:27.959
You, the intelligentsia of the
next generation,

00:06:27.959 --> 00:06:33.185
will be those that preserve
this great treasure of Western

00:06:33.185 --> 00:06:38.319
culture and it is a great
treasure of Western culture.

00:06:38.319 --> 00:06:38.524
Okay.
 

00:06:38.524 --> 00:06:40.000
How are we going to do all of
this?

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:43.675
How are we going to accomplish
these two things on our list of

00:06:43.675 --> 00:06:44.519
agenda here?
 

00:06:44.519 --> 00:06:46.920
What are the mechanics of the
course?

00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:48.310
Did you all get a syllabus?
 

00:06:48.310 --> 00:06:53.569
Everybody's got a syllabus?
 

00:06:53.569 --> 00:06:57.363
The first three or four weeks
or so we'll be following the

00:06:57.363 --> 00:07:00.625
elements of music:
rhythm, melody and harmony--and

00:07:00.625 --> 00:07:01.689
then a test.
 

00:07:01.689 --> 00:07:05.762
Next we will deal with what's
the--arguably--the single most

00:07:05.762 --> 00:07:09.903
important thing when we listen
to any piece of music and that

00:07:09.903 --> 00:07:11.560
is its musical form.
 

00:07:11.560 --> 00:07:13.199
Here is a question for you.
 

00:07:13.199 --> 00:07:16.151
I was thinking about this the
other day as I was preparing the

00:07:16.151 --> 00:07:17.120
lecture for today.
 

00:07:17.120 --> 00:07:21.569
What's the most common type of
musical form in pop music?

00:07:21.569 --> 00:07:26.642
When you listen to pop music do
you ever think about the form of

00:07:26.642 --> 00:07:27.610
the music?
 

00:07:27.610 --> 00:07:33.690
Can anybody name a form of pop
music, any one form?

00:07:33.690 --> 00:07:36.370
Well, maybe verse and chorus?
 

00:07:36.370 --> 00:07:37.290
Think about that.
 

00:07:37.290 --> 00:07:39.699
That shows up in a lot of stuff
and we'll come back to that.

00:07:39.699 --> 00:07:42.762
We'll talk about verse and
chorus when we get to the issue

00:07:42.762 --> 00:07:43.300
of form.
 

00:07:43.300 --> 00:07:47.613
And then toward the end of the
course we will turn to the

00:07:47.613 --> 00:07:49.769
question of musical style.
 

00:07:49.769 --> 00:07:53.553
How does a piece of pop music
differ from a piece of classical

00:07:53.553 --> 00:07:54.050
music?
 

00:07:54.050 --> 00:07:57.305
We sort of all know this
intuitively but can we

00:07:57.305 --> 00:07:58.509
articulate why?
 

00:07:58.509 --> 00:08:01.754
This particular difference
about musical style was driven

00:08:01.754 --> 00:08:03.319
home to me the other day.
 

00:08:03.319 --> 00:08:04.399
It was last Friday.
 

00:08:04.399 --> 00:08:08.779
I was walking across the
campus--maybe you saw this too,

00:08:08.779 --> 00:08:11.009
corner of Elm and College.
 

00:08:11.009 --> 00:08:13.764
There was a large flatbed truck
out there and there were these

00:08:13.764 --> 00:08:15.389
people on this truck getting
you--

00:08:15.389 --> 00:08:17.540
trying to sell you audio
equipment,

00:08:17.540 --> 00:08:20.528
and they had a big banner up
there.

00:08:20.528 --> 00:08:23.110
It said "Pump Up Your
Room."

00:08:23.110 --> 00:08:24.750
Okay?
 

00:08:24.750 --> 00:08:28.379
So then to encourage you to
"pump up your room"

00:08:28.379 --> 00:08:32.335
they had music playing and this
is the kind of music that they

00:08:32.335 --> 00:08:34.279
had on that flatbed truck.
 

00:08:34.279 --> 00:08:37.559
 
 

00:08:37.559 --> 00:08:47.250
&gt;
 

00:08:47.250 --> 00:08:47.537
Okay.
 

00:08:47.537 --> 00:08:50.408
I'm feeling very pumped up at
that particular point

00:08:50.408 --> 00:08:51.960
&gt;
 

00:08:51.960 --> 00:08:54.210
and my cell phone rings.
 

00:08:54.210 --> 00:08:56.538
Okay. My--This is true.
 

00:08:56.538 --> 00:09:01.116
My cell phone rings and because
one has the capacity nowadays to

00:09:01.116 --> 00:09:03.658
select your own ring
tone--right?

00:09:03.658 --> 00:09:07.825
I have mine selected not to
that sound but to Mozart,

00:09:07.825 --> 00:09:10.950
so I hear this sound on my
telephone.

00:09:10.950 --> 00:09:14.259
 
 

00:09:14.259 --> 00:09:17.244
And it will give us a sense of
the difference in style between

00:09:17.244 --> 00:09:18.808
pop music and classical music.
 

00:09:18.808 --> 00:09:22.214
How does this,
what we're about to hear,

00:09:22.214 --> 00:09:23.000
differ?
 

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:24.691
Can you give me,
say, three or four reasons why

00:09:24.691 --> 00:09:26.860
what we're about to hear differs
from what we just heard?

00:09:26.860 --> 00:09:36.594
&gt;
 

00:09:36.594 --> 00:09:38.943
Mozart.
 

00:09:38.943 --> 00:09:49.350
&gt;
 

00:09:49.350 --> 00:09:50.210
Can anyone tell me?
 

00:09:50.210 --> 00:09:53.230
What's the difference between
these two?

00:09:53.230 --> 00:09:56.330
What's the--what did the pop
piece have?

00:09:56.330 --> 00:09:57.870
That's Rave 'Til Dawn.
 

00:09:57.870 --> 00:09:59.524
That's my--I own that album,
I'll have you know,

00:09:59.524 --> 00:10:00.370
Rave 'Til Dawn.
 

00:10:00.370 --> 00:10:01.870
Gentleman back here.
 

00:10:01.870 --> 00:10:05.090
Student: In classical
music there's much more

00:10:05.090 --> 00:10:06.480
attention to detail.
 

00:10:06.480 --> 00:10:09.154
Prof: Yes,
that's probably true as a

00:10:09.154 --> 00:10:11.635
general observation,
whether it comes through

00:10:11.635 --> 00:10:14.642
clearly on these two--
this comparison--I'm not quite

00:10:14.642 --> 00:10:16.830
so sure,
but there--I wouldn't say

00:10:16.830 --> 00:10:19.789
there's a great deal of detail
in the first one.

00:10:19.789 --> 00:10:21.090
There's a lot of repetition.
 

00:10:21.090 --> 00:10:24.517
That's where I--once that gets
going, it goes for a long period

00:10:24.517 --> 00:10:25.070
of time.
 

00:10:25.070 --> 00:10:26.169
Anything else?
 

00:10:26.169 --> 00:10:26.620
Yes?
 

00:10:26.620 --> 00:10:27.269
Student: A melody?
 

00:10:27.269 --> 00:10:28.294
Prof: Oh,
melody.

00:10:28.294 --> 00:10:29.500
Which one had the melody?
 

00:10:29.500 --> 00:10:30.528
Student: The classical
music.

00:10:30.528 --> 00:10:32.028
Prof: Yeah.
 

00:10:32.028 --> 00:10:33.860
&gt;
 

00:10:33.860 --> 00:10:35.659
The first I couldn't pick out
any melody at all.

00:10:35.659 --> 00:10:39.230
It was all what?
 

00:10:39.230 --> 00:10:40.509
Rhythm and beat.
 

00:10:40.509 --> 00:10:41.460
Okay?
 

00:10:41.460 --> 00:10:43.462
So repetitious,
rhythm, beats,

00:10:43.462 --> 00:10:45.190
strong pulsation to it.
 

00:10:45.190 --> 00:10:47.009
What was making that sound?
 

00:10:47.009 --> 00:10:49.929
What were the instruments
playing in the--

00:10:49.929 --> 00:10:50.450
Student: Violins.
 

00:10:50.450 --> 00:10:53.320
Prof: Okay,
in the Mozart there were

00:10:53.320 --> 00:10:56.530
violins, so acoustical
instruments as opposed to

00:10:56.530 --> 00:10:59.879
synthetic sound with regard to
the pop music.

00:10:59.879 --> 00:11:02.868
So what we will be doing is
differentiating pop from

00:11:02.868 --> 00:11:05.798
classical and also
differentiating within styles of

00:11:05.798 --> 00:11:06.970
classical music.
 

00:11:06.970 --> 00:11:09.600
You're driving down the road,
you ...

00:11:09.600 --> 00:11:11.889
who is the FM listener?
 

00:11:11.889 --> 00:11:12.590
Over there ...
 

00:11:12.590 --> 00:11:15.595
You turn on your radio,
your car radio,

00:11:15.595 --> 00:11:19.470
to your FM classical music
station and what number

00:11:19.470 --> 00:11:22.159
approximately would you go to?
 

00:11:22.159 --> 00:11:25.149
Student: In New Haven?
 

00:11:25.149 --> 00:11:26.966
Prof: Yeah,
okay, or anywhere,

00:11:26.966 --> 00:11:28.379
your hometown,
but just--

