00:29:07.484 --> 00:29:09.150
Beethoven Fifth Symphony.
 

00:29:09.150 --> 00:29:13.435
Here's something else and I
guess it's a quiz question I

00:29:13.435 --> 00:29:17.799
think I'm asking you there,
and it has to do about a home

00:29:17.799 --> 00:29:18.578
pitch.
 

00:29:18.578 --> 00:29:25.557
Music gravitates around a home
pitch and in the Beethoven Fifth

00:29:25.557 --> 00:29:30.058
Symphony &lt;&lt;music
playing&gt;&gt;

00:29:30.058 --> 00:29:31.308
we still haven't gotten the
home pitch.

00:29:31.308 --> 00:29:33.220
We go that far and we still
haven't heard the home pitch.

00:29:33.220 --> 00:29:35.038
Can anybody sing the home pitch?
 

00:29:35.038 --> 00:29:36.816
&gt;
 

00:29:36.816 --> 00:29:39.480
&gt;
 

00:29:39.480 --> 00:29:43.665
But he hasn't given it to us
and maybe that's why this sounds

00:29:43.665 --> 00:29:48.808
so disjunct and so unsettled,
apart from the skippy nature of

00:29:48.808 --> 00:29:51.589
the melody,
is that we are not given at the

00:29:51.589 --> 00:29:54.410
outset the home pitch whereas
with the Ninth Symphony,

00:29:54.410 --> 00:29:59.338
&gt;
 

00:29:59.338 --> 00:30:01.463
second phrase,
that's the home pitch there and

00:30:01.463 --> 00:30:03.730
we all feel sort of secure in
that home pitch.

00:30:03.730 --> 00:30:06.951
There's another reason I think
these two sound differently and

00:30:06.951 --> 00:30:08.220
that is the following.
 

00:30:08.220 --> 00:30:11.910
What's the direction generally
of Beethoven's Fifth Symphony?

00:30:11.910 --> 00:30:16.490
&gt;
 

00:30:16.490 --> 00:30:17.759
Student: Down.
 

00:30:17.759 --> 00:30:18.220
Prof: Down.
 

00:30:18.220 --> 00:30:18.910
It's generally going down.
 

00:30:18.910 --> 00:30:22.635
So the direction that music
goes can also affect how we feel

00:30:22.635 --> 00:30:26.362
about it, our mood about it,
so I think the next question--I

00:30:26.362 --> 00:30:28.318
play another piece for you.
 

00:30:28.318 --> 00:30:31.535
I want to play this one with
the piano a little bit and I ask

00:30:31.535 --> 00:30:34.000
you the name of the composer of
this piece--

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:37.200
it's a bit less well known but
maybe not--

00:30:37.200 --> 00:30:41.439
what it's called and when in
the history of music it was

00:30:41.439 --> 00:30:42.210
written.
 

00:30:42.210 --> 00:31:00.960
&gt;
 

00:31:00.960 --> 00:31:04.380
Anybody know that piece and the
name of the composer?

00:31:04.380 --> 00:31:04.661
Yeah?
 

00:31:04.661 --> 00:31:06.799
