00:34:14.472 --> 00:34:14.980
here.
 

00:34:14.980 --> 00:34:17.969
What are the two dimensions of
music?

00:34:17.969 --> 00:34:21.514
Think about dimensions of
painting or architecture perhaps

00:34:21.514 --> 00:34:24.190
but what are the two dimensions
of music?

00:34:24.190 --> 00:34:25.969
Have you thought about that?
 

00:34:25.969 --> 00:34:28.760
Can anybody give me one?
 

00:34:28.760 --> 00:34:31.860
Well, pitch--Oh, yeah.
 

00:34:31.860 --> 00:34:33.349
I'm sorry. Okay.
 

00:34:33.349 --> 00:34:34.010
Pitch.
 

00:34:34.010 --> 00:34:36.159
And what would the other one be?
 

00:34:36.159 --> 00:34:37.050
Time.
 

00:34:37.050 --> 00:34:41.010
Okay, pitch and time and pitch
and duration,

00:34:41.010 --> 00:34:42.670
excellent, so those are the two
dimensions of music and well,

00:34:42.670 --> 00:34:45.813
indeed we could even call them
the axes of music because we

00:34:45.813 --> 00:34:48.199
tend to think of pitch on a
vertical axis.

00:34:48.199 --> 00:34:50.715
We talk in terms of high pitch
and low pitch although we'll

00:34:50.715 --> 00:34:53.422
fine tune that next time,
and then we have this idea of

00:34:53.422 --> 00:34:57.061
duration or time,
which we tend to write out in

00:34:57.061 --> 00:35:01.010
symbols that move from your left
to right.

00:35:01.010 --> 00:35:04.413
So what I'd like to do now is
focus on a piece that

00:35:04.413 --> 00:35:07.409
emphasizes--foregrounds--just
the first axis,

00:35:07.409 --> 00:35:08.090
pitch.
 

00:35:08.090 --> 00:35:11.030
Here is a question for you.
 

00:35:11.030 --> 00:35:17.782
How many of you have heard
Richard Strauss's Also Sprach

00:35:17.782 --> 00:35:19.880
Zarathustra?
 

00:35:19.880 --> 00:35:21.480
Okay.
 

00:35:21.480 --> 00:35:24.666
How many--and be courageous
here--how many have not heard

00:35:24.666 --> 00:35:27.570
Richard Strauss's Also Sprach
Zarathustra?

00:35:27.570 --> 00:35:28.960
Raise your hand nice and big.
 

00:35:28.960 --> 00:35:32.699
Okay, the overwhelming majority
of people say they have not.

00:35:32.699 --> 00:35:33.800
Wrong.
 

00:35:33.800 --> 00:35:35.980
You all have heard this many
times.

00:35:35.980 --> 00:35:39.340
It's used continuously as a
movie score, television,

00:35:39.340 --> 00:35:40.659
radio commercials.
 

00:35:40.659 --> 00:35:42.378
It's all over the place,
and as soon as I start to play

00:35:42.378 --> 00:35:44.452
it,
at least once we get in to it,

00:35:44.452 --> 00:35:45.659
you'll say,
"Oh, yeah,

00:35:45.659 --> 00:35:46.260
I've heard that."
 

00:35:46.260 --> 00:35:51.664
So this is a piece by Strauss
where he's trying to resurrect

00:35:51.664 --> 00:35:53.882
the content,
or mirror the content,

00:35:53.882 --> 00:35:55.800
of a philosophical novel by
Friedrich Nietzsche,

00:35:55.800 --> 00:36:00.266
Thus Spoke Zarathustra,
and it's about the unleashing

00:36:00.266 --> 00:36:04.807
of human capacity as it comes
forth from the primordial earth

00:36:04.807 --> 00:36:05.489
here.
 

00:36:05.489 --> 00:36:09.673
And in Strauss in attempting to
do this will use the orchestra

00:36:09.673 --> 00:36:13.378
to depict here in this
particular case perhaps the rise

00:36:13.378 --> 00:36:16.302
of human power,
maybe as metaphorically

00:36:16.302 --> 00:36:20.681
represented by the sun,
so here is Strauss depicting

00:36:20.681 --> 00:36:22.699
the rise of the sun.
 

