00:36:35.500 --> 00:36:35.739
now.
 

00:36:35.739 --> 00:36:44.739
 
 

00:36:44.739 --> 00:36:51.880
&gt;
 

00:36:51.880 --> 00:36:54.666
What that is,
is an organ pipe of the type of

00:36:54.666 --> 00:36:57.389
organ that we have over in
Woolsey Hall,

00:36:57.389 --> 00:37:01.768
thirty-two feet tall,
this gigantic sound of

00:37:01.768 --> 00:37:04.010
&gt;
 

00:37:04.010 --> 00:37:06.070
down there so that's what he's
trying to set up.

00:37:06.070 --> 00:37:07.280
Okay?
 

00:37:07.280 --> 00:37:11.422
Then a brass instrument enters
and what is the name of this

00:37:11.422 --> 00:37:12.780
brass instrument?
 

00:37:12.780 --> 00:37:35.710
&gt;
 

00:37:35.710 --> 00:37:37.289
And a percussion instrument.
 

00:37:37.289 --> 00:37:54.090
&gt;
 

00:37:54.090 --> 00:37:59.570
So the brass instrument is
the--is a--trumpet.

00:37:59.570 --> 00:38:00.219
Okay?
 

00:38:00.219 --> 00:38:01.099
That's what that is.
 

00:38:01.099 --> 00:38:02.070
It's coming up there.
 

00:38:02.070 --> 00:38:04.170
Let's talk about what we've
done on the board here.

00:38:04.170 --> 00:38:10.360
We can see we have these low
pitches, &gt;

00:38:10.360 --> 00:38:11.340
What did I just sing?
 

00:38:11.340 --> 00:38:13.340
&gt;
 

00:38:13.340 --> 00:38:14.914
Almost the same sounding pitch.
 

00:38:14.914 --> 00:38:15.269
Right?
 

00:38:15.269 --> 00:38:16.079
Well, we'll talk about this.
 

00:38:16.079 --> 00:38:17.500
This is called an octave.
 

00:38:17.500 --> 00:38:18.719
&gt;
 

00:38:18.719 --> 00:38:21.639
It has to do with frequency
ratios that we'll go in to a

00:38:21.639 --> 00:38:22.860
little bit next time.
 

00:38:22.860 --> 00:38:25.730
So he's coming up initially
just through octaves.

00:38:25.730 --> 00:38:27.579
&gt;
 

00:38:27.579 --> 00:38:30.139
Then the next pitch on the
trumpet &gt;

00:38:30.139 --> 00:38:32.969
is actually an interval of a
fifth.

00:38:32.969 --> 00:38:34.440
&gt;
 

00:38:34.440 --> 00:38:35.929
That's a fourth
&gt;

00:38:35.929 --> 00:38:38.010
but it happens to produce an
octave &gt;

00:38:38.010 --> 00:38:39.639
against that.
 

00:38:39.639 --> 00:38:41.949
Then the first time
&gt;

00:38:41.949 --> 00:38:45.927
so he came up a major third
there and then quickly backed

00:38:45.927 --> 00:38:50.260
off with just a half step below
it, which completely gave it a

00:38:50.260 --> 00:38:51.610
different feel.
 

00:38:51.610 --> 00:38:54.208
So a bright,
shiny major and then dark

00:38:54.208 --> 00:38:54.769
minor.
 

00:38:54.769 --> 00:38:57.440
&gt;
 

00:38:57.440 --> 00:38:59.769
Then a percussion instrument
came in.

00:38:59.769 --> 00:39:03.710
Anybody know what that was?
 

00:39:03.710 --> 00:39:05.639
Okay.
 

00:39:05.639 --> 00:39:07.420
Tell me what it was.
 

00:39:07.420 --> 00:39:08.322
Nice and loud.
 

00:39:08.322 --> 00:39:09.550
Yell it out there.
 

00:39:09.550 --> 00:39:10.070
Student: Timpani?
 

00:39:10.070 --> 00:39:12.010
Prof: Timpani or as it's
sometimes called a kettle drum,

00:39:12.010 --> 00:39:14.820
and it was playing two
different pitches,

00:39:14.820 --> 00:39:17.150
actually sort of playing this
pitch and this pitch,

00:39:17.150 --> 00:39:20.159
the octave and then the fifth.
 

00:39:20.159 --> 00:39:25.188
The fifth degree of the scale
after the tonic is the next most

00:39:25.188 --> 00:39:28.980
important and it's called the
dominant note.

00:39:28.980 --> 00:39:29.750
Okay?
 

00:39:29.750 --> 00:39:32.230
So that's what that is in that
particular question.

00:39:32.230 --> 00:39:38.920
So the timpani comes in and it
goes crazy &gt;

00:39:38.920 --> 00:39:42.255
and comes back to the tonic at
which point the trumpet takes

00:39:42.255 --> 00:39:42.989
over again.
 

00:39:42.989 --> 00:39:45.469
So let's listen to just a
little bit more and I

00:39:45.469 --> 00:39:46.980
think--Well, let's listen.
 

00:39:46.980 --> 00:39:48.699
I forget where we left off.
 

00:39:48.699 --> 00:40:02.010
&gt;
 

00:40:02.010 --> 00:40:05.755
Now at this point what happens
is the trumpet

00:40:05.755 --> 00:40:07.630
&gt;
 

00:40:07.630 --> 00:40:08.409
all the way up there.
 

00:40:08.409 --> 00:40:09.519
It's going to jump way, way up.
 

00:40:09.519 --> 00:40:13.090
So let's listen to that.
 

00:40:13.090 --> 00:40:34.280
&gt;
 

00:40:34.280 --> 00:40:36.559
What's happening and interests
me acoustically,

00:40:36.559 --> 00:40:38.925
and again we'll come back to
it, is that we're getting up

00:40:38.925 --> 00:40:40.940
toward here,
and notice how these pitches in

00:40:40.940 --> 00:40:43.789
terms of the ratio frequencies
are getting very close together.

00:40:43.789 --> 00:40:47.949
So we're going to go
&gt;

00:40:47.949 --> 00:40:49.190
You sing the next note.
 

00:40:49.190 --> 00:40:51.980
&gt;
 

00:40:51.980 --> 00:40:52.860
There it is up there.
 

00:40:52.860 --> 00:40:53.469
Okay? Good.
 

00:40:53.469 --> 00:40:54.329
You got it. Come on. Louder.
 

00:40:54.329 --> 00:40:55.849
&gt;
 

00:40:55.849 --> 00:40:57.150
Coraggio!
 

00:40:57.150 --> 00:40:58.150
Okay. So there we are there.
 

00:40:58.150 --> 00:41:00.579
My question on the quiz is
what's this one called?

00:41:00.579 --> 00:41:05.920
&gt;
 

00:41:05.920 --> 00:41:06.233
Okay.
 

00:41:06.233 --> 00:41:09.989
So this is a leading tone going
in to that particular note.

00:41:09.989 --> 00:41:24.911
So let's listen to here again
just the very end of this with

00:41:24.911 --> 00:41:38.063
the spectacular sound of the
orchestra, &lt;&lt;music

00:41:38.063 --> 00:41:42.869
playing&gt;&gt;
 

00:41:42.869 --> 00:41:45.884
and there at the end you could
hear the organ a little bit

00:41:45.884 --> 00:41:46.360
better.
 

00:41:46.360 --> 00:41:51.398
So that's how using some of
these basic ratios gives us this

00:41:51.398 --> 00:41:56.010
primordial type of music and
it's quite spectacular.

00:41:56.010 --> 00:41:59.393
It's quite spectacular because
here in the 1890s we have the

00:41:59.393 --> 00:42:02.202
apex of the Western classical
orchestra, this big,

00:42:02.202 --> 00:42:04.210
beautiful, powerful instrument.
 

00:42:04.210 --> 00:42:04.753
Okay.
 

00:42:04.753 --> 00:42:09.550
We've talked a little bit about
pitch here.

00:42:09.550 --> 00:42:15.815
Let's go on to talk about the
other axis of music and that is

00:42:15.815 --> 00:42:18.010
rhythm or duration.
 

00:42:18.010 --> 00:42:22.773
Now in music as you probably
know--we've already talked a

00:42:22.773 --> 00:42:27.880
little bit about this--we have
the importance of the beat.

00:42:27.880 --> 00:42:31.726
The beat's very important in
music and generally speaking,

00:42:31.726 --> 00:42:33.820
in music, we divide the beat.
 

00:42:33.820 --> 00:42:35.530
We organize it into groups.
 

00:42:35.530 --> 00:42:37.210
The beat's kind of like the
heartbeat.

00:42:37.210 --> 00:42:42.989
It's kind of like the basic
pulse of &gt;

00:42:42.989 --> 00:42:47.010
but, given our psychological
makeup,

00:42:47.010 --> 00:42:49.585
we tend to divide these up into
units: so generally two and

00:42:49.585 --> 00:42:52.846
generally three,
and if we have groups of two we

00:42:52.846 --> 00:42:56.117
call that duple meter;
groups of three we call that of

00:42:56.117 --> 00:42:57.119
course triple meter.
 

00:42:57.119 --> 00:42:58.510
How do we indicate these?
 

00:42:58.510 --> 00:43:00.679
Well, by some kind of
conducting pattern.

00:43:00.679 --> 00:43:01.429
We'll come back to this.
 

00:43:01.429 --> 00:43:02.820
You'll all be conducting in
here.

00:43:02.820 --> 00:43:08.637
So duple is just one,
two, one two,

00:43:08.637 --> 00:43:14.969
one two, one,
&gt;

00:43:14.969 --> 00:43:17.034
, one strong beat,
one weak beat,

00:43:17.034 --> 00:43:18.467
strong,
weak, strong,

00:43:18.467 --> 00:43:22.420
weak, in that fashion,
and conversely of course triple

00:43:22.420 --> 00:43:24.717
is strong,
weak, weak, strong,

00:43:24.717 --> 00:43:28.769
weak, weak, with two weak beats
between each strong beat.

00:43:28.769 --> 00:43:31.530
So here's a question for you.
 

00:43:31.530 --> 00:43:34.402
Who wrote the musical,
and it's on your quiz there,

00:43:34.402 --> 00:43:35.380
Chicago?
 

00:43:35.380 --> 00:43:36.750
Anybody know the answer to that?
 

00:43:36.750 --> 00:43:37.523
How--Okay.
 

00:43:37.523 --> 00:43:42.170
How many don't know--a rousing
show of hands here--don't know

00:43:42.170 --> 00:43:44.340
who wrote Chicago?
 

00:43:44.340 --> 00:43:45.679
This is amazing to me.
 

00:43:45.679 --> 00:43:48.230
This guy is the stealth bomber
of music.

00:43:48.230 --> 00:43:51.416
How nobody could know the name
of this person that has given us

00:43:51.416 --> 00:43:53.307
so much great music,
Cabaret,

00:43:53.307 --> 00:43:55.530
Chicago,
songs that you go on singing,

00:43:55.530 --> 00:43:58.380
have in your ear all the time,
John Kander,

00:43:58.380 --> 00:44:01.300
lives down in New York City,
writes a lot of this stuff.

00:44:01.300 --> 00:44:06.052
So we're going to listen to a
track out of John Kander's

00:44:06.052 --> 00:44:09.903
Chicago here,
and the question that's at--in

00:44:09.903 --> 00:44:13.260
play at the moment is what's the
meter of this cut from

00:44:13.260 --> 00:44:14.380
Chicago?
 

00:44:14.380 --> 00:44:25.070
&gt;
 

00:44:25.070 --> 00:44:25.465
Okay.
 

00:44:25.465 --> 00:44:28.630
Here's something that may
interest you.

00:44:28.630 --> 00:44:31.570
We'll be playing a lot of pop
music in here but they will

00:44:31.570 --> 00:44:33.670
generally be short clips of pop
music.

00:44:33.670 --> 00:44:38.849
Why is that the case?
 

00:44:38.849 --> 00:44:42.369
For copyright reasons,
that's right.

00:44:42.369 --> 00:44:44.210
So we've heard a passage here.
 

00:44:44.210 --> 00:44:48.030
What was the meter of that
section?

00:44:48.030 --> 00:44:50.215
Gentleman down here,
you seem to be moving with the

00:44:50.215 --> 00:44:51.440
music, which is very good.
 

00:44:51.440 --> 00:44:52.152
What did you think?
 

00:44:52.152 --> 00:44:52.789
Duple or triple?
 

00:44:52.789 --> 00:44:53.849
Student: Duple.
 

00:44:53.849 --> 00:44:55.557
Prof: Okay,
duple.

00:44:55.557 --> 00:44:58.050
Now I would come--That's
correct.

00:44:58.050 --> 00:45:00.811
I would come right back to you
with yeah, you intuited that but

00:45:00.811 --> 00:45:02.860
can you explain to me what you
were hearing?

00:45:02.860 --> 00:45:07.126
What did you hear that allowed
