00:45:07.126 --> 00:45:10.309
that decision,
make that correct decision?

00:45:10.309 --> 00:45:11.639
Any ideas?
 

00:45:11.639 --> 00:45:12.869
Anybody.
 

00:45:12.869 --> 00:45:15.230
Student: Cut time--
Prof: Okay, cut time.

00:45:15.230 --> 00:45:16.007
Student: Accent on one..
 

00:45:16.007 --> 00:45:16.510
Prof: What?
 

00:45:16.510 --> 00:45:19.054
Accent on one,
but what part of the music were

00:45:19.054 --> 00:45:20.130
you listening to?
 

00:45:20.130 --> 00:45:23.829
Student:
&gt;

00:45:23.829 --> 00:45:24.478
Prof: Yeah.
 

00:45:24.478 --> 00:45:25.090
Yeah, that's it.
 

00:45:25.090 --> 00:45:27.570
Somebody's up there going
&gt;

00:45:27.570 --> 00:45:29.992
and it's actually the bass so
we'll be wanting to zero in on

00:45:29.992 --> 00:45:32.170
the bass in a big way in music
&gt;

00:45:32.170 --> 00:45:34.909
because that's oftentimes
giving us much more information

00:45:34.909 --> 00:45:35.789
than the melody.
 

00:45:35.789 --> 00:45:37.210
&gt;
 

00:45:37.210 --> 00:45:39.170
So there we had an example of
duple.

00:45:39.170 --> 00:45:39.860
Let's see.
 

00:45:39.860 --> 00:45:41.260
Have we got another excerpt
here?

00:45:41.260 --> 00:45:43.150
Let's listen to a little bit of
that.

00:45:43.150 --> 00:45:54.130
&gt;
 

00:45:54.130 --> 00:45:56.000
So what about that one?
 

00:45:56.000 --> 00:45:57.230
Student: Triple.
 

00:45:57.230 --> 00:45:57.585
Prof: Yeah.
 

00:45:57.585 --> 00:45:58.079
You know the setup here.
 

00:45:58.079 --> 00:45:59.590
We did duple and now we've got
to do triple.

00:45:59.590 --> 00:46:00.306
Okay.
 

00:46:00.306 --> 00:46:07.050
So that's strong,
weak, weak, in that fashion.

00:46:07.050 --> 00:46:07.679
All right?
 

00:46:07.679 --> 00:46:09.599
Now let's listen to a little
bit more of this,

00:46:09.599 --> 00:46:11.650
and something interesting
happens to the beat.

00:46:11.650 --> 00:46:13.030
It slows down.
 

00:46:13.030 --> 00:46:17.552
What do we call the passage of
music in which the beat slows

00:46:17.552 --> 00:46:18.090
down?
 

00:46:18.090 --> 00:46:19.150
What's being applied?
 

00:46:19.150 --> 00:46:20.489
What's being affected here?
 

00:46:20.489 --> 00:46:22.500
What's being used here?
 

00:46:22.500 --> 00:46:31.809
&gt;
 

00:46:31.809 --> 00:46:34.960
Okay, a very simple word there:
Ritard.

00:46:34.960 --> 00:46:38.010
Okay? So the music is retarded.
 

00:46:38.010 --> 00:46:42.289
We have the pulse being slowed
down and almost like a law of

00:46:42.289 --> 00:46:46.317
physics or something,
now comes a reaction--now John

00:46:46.317 --> 00:46:50.052
Kander makes the music
accelerate so let's watch a

00:46:50.052 --> 00:46:53.179
wonderful example of accelerando
here.

00:46:53.179 --> 00:47:00.313
&gt;
 

00:47:00.313 --> 00:47:04.250
Let me hear it.
 

00:47:04.250 --> 00:47:05.239
Okay.
 

00:47:05.239 --> 00:47:09.637
So at that point the music
begins to speed up with the

00:47:09.637 --> 00:47:10.800
accelerando.
 

00:47:10.800 --> 00:47:11.920
Now &lt;&lt;music
playing&gt;&gt;

00:47:11.920 --> 00:47:14.760
getting close
&gt;

00:47:14.760 --> 00:47:16.190
drive to the end.
 

00:47:16.190 --> 00:47:17.699
Do you ever notice this in
musical compositions?

00:47:17.699 --> 00:47:19.909
Keep an eye out for this,
particularly in pop music.

00:47:19.909 --> 00:47:22.760
They've got an idea but they've
got to fill up a track.

00:47:22.760 --> 00:47:27.010
They really need a good three
minutes and thirty seconds here.

00:47:27.010 --> 00:47:30.067
They'll have something going
and then almost unbeknownst to

00:47:30.067 --> 00:47:33.177
you they will take that and lift
it up in terms of the pitch

00:47:33.177 --> 00:47:33.809
content.
 

00:47:33.809 --> 00:47:38.213
What is that called when you
change the fundamental pitch in

00:47:38.213 --> 00:47:41.500
a piece, going to a different
pitch level?

00:47:41.500 --> 00:47:43.190
Anybody know about that?
 

00:47:43.190 --> 00:47:46.326
Called modulation and this is
sort of where we'll be really,

00:47:46.326 --> 00:47:48.559
really four months from now,
modulation.

00:47:48.559 --> 00:47:50.619
It's very subtle.
 

00:47:50.619 --> 00:47:54.541
A lot of what we were doing
today is very straightforward,

00:47:54.541 --> 00:47:58.737
the idea of duple versus triple
meter, but most modulations we

00:47:58.737 --> 00:48:00.320
don't usually hear.
 

00:48:00.320 --> 00:48:04.643
So let's listen to--We've got
two more cuts to do and then

00:48:04.643 --> 00:48:06.010
